'''Saarah Hameed Ahmed''' (born 22 April 1989) is an Indian [[Pilot (aeronautics)|pilot]] from [[Bangalore]], [[Karnataka]]. {{As of|March 2015}}, she worked for [[SpiceJet]].<ref name="inspiration" /> According to a news report published by ''[[Hindustan Times]]'', Saarah was the only known woman [[Muslim]] pilot in Indian aviation sector {{as of|March 2015|lc=y}}.<ref name="inspiration" /> ''[[The Hindu]]'' lists her as the first Muslim woman pilot in [[Karnataka]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/bangalore/a-flight-away-from-religious-stereotypes/article6971659.ece|title=A Flight Away from Religious Stereotypes|last=Deepika|first=K.C.|date=8 March 2015|work=The Hindu|access-date=1 September 2016|via=}}</ref>
Saarah later clarified that she had never claimed to be the first Indian Muslim woman pilot and was simply one amongst a few Muslim women pilots. She further clarified that she had never mentioned anything about Islamophobia or being treated badly.<ref>{{cite web|title=I never said any such thing as Islamophobia, Indian female Muslim pilot clarifies|url=http://www.siasat.com/news/i-never-said-any-such-thing-islamophobia-875778/|website=The Siasat Daily|date=27 November 2015}}</ref>
== Background == Saarah Sabah Hameed Ahmed was born and raised in [[Bangalore]], Karnataka. After completing a [[Pre-university course|PUC]] at Jyothi Nivas College, in 2007 Ahmed enrolled in the Paris Air Flight Training School in [[Vero Beach, Florida]].<ref name="flight school">{{cite news|last1=Siraj|first1=M A|title=She flies high with her wings of passion|url=http://www.deccanherald.com/content/363808/she-flies-high-her-wings.html|accessdate=24 September 2015|publisher=Deccan Herald|date=19 October 2013|location=Bengaluru, India}}</ref> In the post [[September 11 attacks|9/11]] period of [[Islamophobia]], she claims that most Muslim students were being denied [[Visa policy of the United States|US Visas]], but she had little difficulty obtaining one.
According to Ahmed's father, in the traditional community in which she was raised, a woman's responsibility is to her home and children, with few seeking outside jobs without an escort.<ref name="inspiration" /> Ahmed did not initially receive support within the community and her family tried to discourage her, but they relented when she insisted and a friend of her father's who is a pilot with [[Southwest Airlines]] offered reassurances.<ref name="inspiration" /> After a year of study and logging 200 flight hours, Ahmed received her commercial pilot's license in 2008.<ref name="flight school" /> She returned to India and undertook the process to convert her license to an Indian certification, which required both a waiting period and additional training in [[Lithuania]] to learn about specific [[Airliner|commercial aircraft]] types.<ref name="flight school" /> She has also said of the commercial aviation field that "male monopoly has been broken but parity in numbers would take some more time."<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.fijitimes.com/story.aspx?id=366948|title=Women Leaders of the Skies|last=|first=|date=15 August 2016|work=The Fiji Times|access-date=31 August 2016|via=}}</ref>
== Career == After completion of her [[Bachelor of Business Administration]] and some 1200 flying hours, she was recruited by [[SpiceJet]] in 2010 as a commercial pilot.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.indiatimes.com/news/india/india-s-first-muslim-woman-pilot-says-she-faces-a-lot-of-islamophobia-247637.html|title=India's First Muslim Woman Pilot Says She Faces A Lot Of Islamophobia|last=Abraham|first=Bobins|date=23 November 2015|work=India Times|access-date=31 August 2016|via=}}</ref> She was the first Muslim woman to be chosen in the [[aviation]] sector and for nearly two years, remained the only female Muslim pilot out of the 600 women employed in the Indian Aviation Industry.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://islamicvoice.com/saara-hameed-indias-first-muslim-woman-pilot/|title=Saara Hameed – India’s First Muslim Woman Pilot|last=Siraj|first=Maqbool Ahmed|date=15 November 2013|work=Islamic Voice|access-date=31 August 2016|via=}}</ref> Her accomplishment has been inspirational in her community, encouraging other Muslim women to enroll in pilot training.<ref name=inspiration>{{cite news|last1=Mondal|first1=Sudipto|title=India’s only woman Muslim pilot has a message to share|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/india/india-s-only-woman-muslim-pilot-has-a-message-to-share/story-iiUTPOrYQxhrs0Mrx1LtUK.html|accessdate=24 September 2015|newspaper=Hindustan Times|date=9 March 2015|location=Bengaluru, India}}</ref>
